        "MLA": "Author's last name and page number (Smith 123)",
        "APA": "Author's last name, year, and page number for direct quotes (Smith, 2020, p. 123)"
      },
      {
        "aspect": "Reference List",
        "MLA": "Called \"Works Cited\", alphabetical by author's last name",
        "APA": "Called \"References\", alphabetical by author's last name"
      },
      {
        "aspect": "Date Format",
        "MLA": "Day Month Year (e.g., 15 May 2023)",
        "APA": "Year, Month Day (e.g., 2023, May 15)"
      },
      {
        "aspect": "Page Numbers",
        "MLA": "Author's last name and page number in header of every page",
        "APA": "Page number in header of every page, with running head on first page"
      }
    ],
    "general_formatting": {
      "font": "Both typically use 12-point Times New Roman or similar serif font",
      "line_spacing": "Both use double-spacing throughout the document",
      "margins": "Both use 1-inch margins on all sides"
    }
  },
  "conclusion": "MLA and APA are two different citation styles with distinct rules for formatting papers, citing sources, and creating reference lists. The choice between them usually depends on the academic discipline and instructor preferences."
